{
  "texts": [
    "By an elementary degree computation [ABHS25, Lemma 9.20], there are elements [𝜆 𝑚] ∈ 𝑅 Q (𝑑), 1 ≤ 𝑚 ≤ 𝑑, such that the 𝑖th component of 𝜃 𝑑 [𝜆 𝑚] is |surj(𝑖, 𝑚)|, see Theorem 3.5.",
    "The same example shows that the vectors 𝜃 𝑑 [𝜆 1],..., 𝜃 𝑑 [𝜆 𝑑] are linearly independent, hence 𝜃 𝑑 is surjective for all 𝑑.To see that 𝜃 𝑑 is injective, and hence an isomorphism, we work by induction over 𝑑.",
    "In the initial case of 𝑑 = 1, we have equivalencesHom Exc 1 * (Sp 𝜔,Sp) (𝑃 1 ℎ S, 𝑃 1 ℎ S) 𝜕 1 -→ Hom Sp (𝜕 1 (𝑃 1 ℎ S), 𝜕 1 (𝑃 1 ℎ S)), ≃ Hom Sp (S, S),by the classification of homogeneous functors, since 𝐷 1 ℎ S ≃ 𝑃 1 ℎ S. Taking 𝜋 0 gives the required ring isomorphism 𝜃 1: 𝑅 Q (1) → Q.For the induction step, assume that 𝜃 𝑑-1 is an isomorphism.",
    "Since 𝜕 𝑖 𝑃 𝑑-1 ≃ 𝜕 𝑖 for 1 ≤ 𝑖 ≤ 𝑑 -1 and 𝜕 𝑑 𝑃 𝑑-1 ≃ 0, there is a commutative diagram𝑅 Q (𝑑) Q 𝑑 𝑅 Q (𝑑 -1) Q 𝑑-1 𝜃 𝑑 𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑 -1)⊗Q (𝑖 𝑑 -1) * 𝜃 𝑑 -1where (𝑖 𝑑-1) *: Q 𝑑 → Q 𝑑-1 is projection onto the first (𝑑 -1) factors.",
    "The above square induces a map θ𝑑: ker(𝜋 0 (𝑃 𝑑-1) ⊗ Q) -→ ker((𝑖 𝑑-1) *), on vertical kernels."
  ]
